#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Descending",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 4 | E5",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Descending]

,aim: [
Descend the aircraft at various rates and in various configurations to a predetermined altitude whilst maintaining balance and; formally introduce the full takeoff sequence.
]

,overview: [
The student enters, maintains, and levels off from a range of descent profiles — cruise, powered, glide, and approach — using the PAT workcycles. This lesson also includes the formal introduction of Element 8 (Take Off): the student manages the complete takeoff sequence for the first time under instructor supervision, including the pre-takeoff safety brief. Pre-flight inspection responsibility transfers to the student and the documentation becomes the student's responsibility to complete.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Recall the four forces and their interaction during a steady descent
- Explain that reduced thrust creates the descent — not reduced lift
- Describe the factors affecting descent and glide performance (thrust, flap, wind, density altitude)
- Explain the effect of flap on descent angle, rate, and airspeed
- Apply a rule of thumb to estimate top of descent point
- Explain engine cooling considerations during prolonged glides
- Describe the emergency descent procedure: when it applies; entry technique; target airspeed; configuration; communication

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Conduct cruise, powered, glide, and approach descents using the PAT workcycle
- Maintain nominated descent profile within ±10 kts and heading ±5°, in balance
- Manage flap configuration during descent and observe effect on profile
- Level off at a nominated altitude using the PAT workcycle with correct anticipation
- Conduct a complete takeoff sequence under close instruction (E8)
- Deliver a pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi
- Complete preflight documentation and inspection independently

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [TEM] Engine overcooling during glides; terrain and traffic awareness below
- [SA] Mental map of traffic — use alerted see-and-avoid to maintain SA
- [HF] Ear pressure during descent; recognise blockage symptoms
- [CRM] Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief clearly and confirm crew acknowledgement before taxi
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Human Factors — ear problems, vision, SA *(Pg 3, 10, 13–16)*
- Aerodynamics — drag, flap effect, glide performance *(Pg 122, 157–159)*
- Aeroplane Performance — VSI, glide performance *(Pg 224)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, access to electronic briefing, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Engine overcooling in prolonged glide; terrain in descent area
- [SA] Alerted see-and-avoid; maintain SA
- [HF] Ear pressure on descent; Valsalva manoeuvre; report blockage early
- [TEM/CRM] Pre-takeoff safety brief: purpose and structure

*Forces in a Descent* (10 minutes)
- Four forces in a steady descent; forward component of weight replaces lost thrust
- Factors affecting descent performance: power, flap, turning, headwind vs tailwind
- Best glide speed: best lift/drag, maximum range

*Types of Descent* (5 mins)
- Cruise descent: ~105–110 kt, 5000 RPM
- Powered descent: ~90–100 kt, 4000 RPM
- Glide descent: 70 kt, idle RPM — clear engine every 1000 ft
- Approach descent: ~70 kt, flap 2, 3000 RPM

*Attitude Flying in the Descent* (5 minutes)
- Entry: PAT (reduce power, hold attitude until airspeed stabilises, then set descent attitude, trim)
- Level-off: PAT — power leads because inertia causes continued sink

*Flap Effect* (2 minutes)
- Increasing flap increases rate and angle of descent; reduces best glide range
- Any descent with flap requires more power to maintain the same airspeed

*Emergency Descent* (3 minutes)
- When it applies: fire, smoke or fumes in the cockpit where rapid altitude loss is required; or if oxygen were required at altitude
- Entry: published emergency descent procedure from the POH; or if not published - power idle, roll to 45° AOB, pitch for 100-110 knots in a descending turn; control AoB and pitch carefully to avoid spiral dive
- Communication: MAYDAY or PAN as appropriate; advise ATC (or transmit blind on CTAF/Centre) of intentions

*E8 Introduction — Full Takeoff* (10 minutes)
- Pre-takeoff safety brief: intentions on engine failure during roll and after takeoff
- Directional control on the roll: look far ahead, right rudder as power applied
- Set takeoff attitude: nosewheel just off the ground, wait for flying speed
- Maintain climbout attitude: target Vy after lift-off; trim as speed stabilises
]
,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review weather, NOTAMs with the student, note any hazards
- Introduce the EFATO brief structure; student to deliver before taxi
- Observe student lead the pre-flight inspection and complete documentation independently

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Lead pre-flight inspection; independently complete the documentation
- Conduct start, taxi, runup, and all checklists to takeoff
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi (with instructor guidance)
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff Progression — Lesson 4*]
Student manages the complete takeoff sequence with instructor supervision. Instructor is ready to intervene but does not assist unless required.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- All turns to be flown by instructor; student manages all straight climbs and descents.
- Cruise descent: 5000 RPM, ~105–110 kt, attitude, trim, heading ±5°
- Powered descent: 4000 RPM, ~90–100 kt, attitude, trim
- Glide descent: idle RPM, 70 kt, trim; clear engine every 1000 ft
- Approach descent: 3000 RPM, flap 2, ~70 kt, trim
- Flap effect: demonstrate increased rate and angle with flap extension
- Level-off: PAT — power, attitude, trim
- Emergency descent: patter entry; patter careful attitude control to avoid spiral dive

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Takeoff: student conducts full sequence per E8 progression above
- Cruise, powered, glide, and approach descents: initiated from level flight using PAT
- Deviation correction: recognise ±10 kt airspeed or ±10° heading; correct using LARI
- Flap in descent: deploy flaps and observe effect on profile
- Level-off: apply PAT; aim for ±150 ft of nominated altitude
- Coordination: ball centred ±1/4 width throughout
]

,common_errors:[
- *No power on level-off*: Power leads the level-off — PAT; the nose rises only after power is added.
- *Airspeed mismanagement*: Set the attitude; do not chase airspeed.
- *Engine overcooling in glide*: Clear the engine every 1000 ft
- *Directional drift on climbout (E8)*: Look at a reference point well ahead; anticipate and apply right rudder smoothly with power.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes their first full takeoff and any descent challenges.
- *Instructor Feedback* (5 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (P, S, C, or NC) for both E5 and E8 elements.
  - Highlight takeoff strengths and areas to refine.
  - Discuss TEM: "You noticed the engine cooling down and took action."
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "How would you control descent to aim for a point on the ground? How would a strong headwind affect your glide?"
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
  #text(size:12pt)[*Progressing — may advance to Lesson 5*]
- *Descent performance*: Airspeed ±10 kts, heading ±10° across at least three descent types
- *Level-off*: Achieves nominated altitude ±200 ft; PAT workcycle applied with minor prompting
- *Flap management*: Operates flaps within limits independently; observes and partially describes effect
- *E8 — Takeoff*: Completes ground roll with light guidance; achieves safe lift-off; brief delivered with minor prompting
- *Documentation*: Completes preflight documentation with minimal guidance
- *Airmanship*: Applies engine cooling procedures with occasional reminders

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo*]
- *Descent performance*: Airspeed ±10 kts (S), heading ±5° (S) across all descent types
- *Level-off*: Achieves nominated altitude ±150 ft (S) using PAT workcycle
- *Flap management*: Operates flaps within limits; observes and describes effect on profile
- *E8 — Takeoff*: Maintains directional control; achieves safe lift-off and climbout; delivers pre-takeoff brief with prompting
- *Documentation*: Completes preflight documentation independently
- *Knowledge*: Explains descent types and when each is used; explains flap effect on glide
- *Airmanship*: Clears engine during glide
- *Outcome*: Recorded in student records (P, S, C, or NC) with comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible, ceiling >2000 ft, wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct manoeuvres above 1000 ft AGL; maintain terrain clearance during descents
- *Emergency Procedures*: EFATO brief completed; forced landing area pre-selected
- *TEM*:
  - Monitor for student ear discomfort during descent; stop descending if reported
  - Ensure engine cleared every 1000 ft during glide
  - Monitor traffic especially below current altitude
  - Maintain SA regarding controlled airspace boundaries
  - Monitor for student anxiety or disorientation; pause, assess and continue or cut lesson short if needed
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pages 122, 157–159 (forces in descent, drag, glide performance, flap effect)
  - Human Factors: Pages 3, 10, 13–16 (IMSAFE, ear pressure, vision)
  - Aeroplane Performance: Pages 224 (VSI, glide performance)
- Reflect on lesson: "How would you control your descent to aim for a specific point on the ground? How would a strong headwind change your glide?"
]
)

